    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tip. what do you mean about trimming the roots though? i'm scared i'll hurt it. is there any specific way i should handle them so they stay healthy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the fear of cutting your fiddle leaf fig's roots is absolutely understandable! It's like trying to untangle a knot of yarn without snapping the thread; you just need to be gentle and precise. Here's how to do it without hurting the plant:\n\nFirst, **scrape the soil off** the roots with your fingernails or a small knife, being careful not to dig too deep or slice into the white, fleshy part of the root. If you see any roots that are **longer than 1/2 inch** or look mushy and brown, **trim them off** with clean, sharp scissors. Think of it like trimming the dead ends of a branch; the plant will grow new, healthy roots from the healthy ones.\n\n**Crucially, never cut the main stem or the crown** of the plant! That's the part where the leaves attach. If you cut that, the plant will just grow a new stem from the stump, and it might not even take root. Also, **don't leave any roots hanging out** of the soil; they need to be buried deep enough to breathe, but not so deep that they rot.\n\nAfter trimming, **replant the plant",
      "source": "target",
